<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>The multiplier effect is smaller when:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The MPC is larger</option>
            <option letter="b">The tax rate is lower</option>
            <option letter="c">Imports are higher</option>
            <option letter="d">Government spending increases</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Higher imports create more leakages from the circular flow of income, reducing the multiplier effect as more spending flows out of the domestic economy.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which of the following would increase velocity in the equation of exchange?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">An increase in the money supply</option>
            <option letter="b">A decrease in nominal GDP</option>
            <option letter="c">Financial innovation reducing cash holdings</option>
            <option letter="d">An increase in bank reserves</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Financial innovations that reduce the need to hold cash increase the velocity of money as each dollar is used more frequently in transactions.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>In the long run, an increase in the money supply will:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increase real GDP</option>
            <option letter="b">Decrease real GDP</option>
            <option letter="c">Increase only the price level</option>
            <option letter="d">Decrease only the price level</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>According to the classical dichotomy, in the long run, changes in the money supply affect only nominal variables (like prices) and not real variables (like GDP).</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which fiscal policy action would have the largest multiplier effect?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">An increase in government spending</option>
            <option letter="b">A decrease in income taxes</option>
            <option letter="c">An increase in transfer payments</option>
            <option letter="d">A decrease in corporate taxes</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Government spending has the largest multiplier effect because it directly adds to aggregate demand, while tax changes and transfers work through changes in disposable income.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
